These Italians nobly served Russia!

While the Germans were mainly engaged in politics and warfare in the Russian Empire, the Italians devoted themselves entirely to culture.

Aristotele Fioravanti, a native of Bologna, built the Assumption Cathedral in the Moscow Kremlin, which, later, became one of the most important Orthodox churches in the country. In addition, Prince Ivan III engaged the Italian to work on the Cannon Yard, as well as the Moscow Kremlin walls and towers.

Famous architect Bartolomeo Rastrelli managed to work under as many as seven Russian emperors and empresses. Among his most famous works are the Great Peterhof Palace, the Great Catherine Palace in Tsarskoye Selo and the Winter Palace in St. Petersburg.

Italian composer, conductor and teacher Giuseppe Sarti served as Kapellmeister at the court of Catherine II. He wrote eight operas, a ballet and some 30 vocal and chorus works, as well as staging a musical spectacle titled ‚ÄòThe Early Reign of Oleg‚Äô, for which the empress herself had written the libretto.

And it was outstanding Italian architect Carlo Rossi who created that impressive image of St. Petersburg, which today can be admired by tourists and residents of the cultural capital of Russia. The Italian designed such grandiose projects as the Mikhailovsky Palace, the General Staff building with the triumphal arch on Palace Square, the Senate and Synod buildings on Senate Square.
